[normal]3.3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Cyclists under threat: a survey of Oxford cyclists' perceptions of risk[bold],[bold] HEALTH EDUCATION JOURNAL VOL 51/4, 1992, 
[normal]Sissons Joshi, Smith, 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.3.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Description: - 
[normal]“
[normal]FIFTY regular cyclists in Oxford kept a diary over
[normal] 
[normal]14 days in early June 1992 
[normal]and recorded 404
[normal] 
[normal]incidents which made them feel at risk. 
[normal]This[bold] [bold]constituted a rate of 0.9 incidents per cyclist per[bold] [bold]day of cycling[bold]. Fear was mostly induced by
[normal] 
[normal]other road users. Cars were blamed in 45.3 per
[normal] 
[normal]cent of the incidents, followed by buses (14.6 per
[normal] 
[normal]cent), vans (8.4 per cent) and other cyclists (6.4
[normal] 
[normal]per cent). Buses make up less than 5 per cent of
[normal] 
[normal]the city-centre traffic but were involved in 27 per
[normal] 
[normal]cent of the incidents rated as 'moderately to extremely
[normal] 
[normal]threatening' by the cyclists. 
[normal]Seventy-one[bold] [bold]per ce[bold]nt of the incidents took place in 'straight[bold]-[bold]ahead'[bold] [bold]sit[bold]uations with only 19 per cent at [bold]junctions and roundabouts[bold]…
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.3.2.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Discussion[bold]: [bold]The finding that, for this group of regular cyclists,
[normal] 
[normal]threatening incidents on the roads were experienced at the
[normal] 
[normal]rate of nearly 
[normal]one incident per cyclist per day cycled,
[normal] 
[normal]suggests that there is likely to be a considerable disincentive
[normal] 
[normal]to cycling. 
[normal]…
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The picture of risk derived from the diaries deviates somewhat from local accident figures. It is not clear what weight should be given 
[normal]to the official statistics on accidents as it is well accepted that cycle accidents, including those involving serious injury, are massively under-reported 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The discrepancies between the figures obtained from the diaries and those of police record data ar[bold]e reminders of the subjectivity of accident notation and witness testimony[bold]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]If a cyclist swerves to avoid
[normal] [bold]an unexpected pothole, an 
[normal]ensuing accident
[normal] with an offside
[normal] [bold]vehicle could be attributed either to 
[normal]cyclist error
[normal], to motorist
[normal] [bold]error or to road conditi
[normal]ons.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The diary figures also deviate from national accident figures produced by the Department of Transport, which give more emphasis to vehicles turning left and right, and less emphasis to parked vehicles[bold]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In its document Pedal Cyclist Casualties-1, 
[normal]the Department of Transport does warn the reader about the possible unreliability 
[normal]of their
[normal] data due to the underreporting of cycle accidents to the police
[normal], which
[normal] form the basis for their figures.  Furthermore, local figures may well differ from national fi
[normal]gures because of variations in traffic density and type, and local provision (or lack of provision) for cyclists. Also it must be noted that the diarists in the study reported here were over 23-years-old and were experienced and regular cyclists. As such t
[normal]hey were likely to anticipate the infamous problem areas for cyclists - that is, junctions and roundabouts. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]However
[normal] 
[normal]it is possible that cycle proficiency education has overestimated[bold] 
[normal]the risk to cyclists at intersections and roundabouts and[bold] 
[normal]underestimated the risk in straight-ahead situations. [bold]&#xa0;[bold]Hospital[bold]-[bold]based[bold] [bold]studies of cycle accidents not only suggest a much[bold] [bold]larger number of accidents but also a different pattern of[bold] [bold]accidents than that indicated by police records. It is[bold] [bold]interesting to note [bold]that an Australian study examining the[bold] [bold]characteristics of fatal, as compared to total, bicycle accidents[bold] [bold]finds that fatal accidents are less likely to be at[bold] [bold]intersections than a[bold]re non-fatal accidents.[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]3.4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]We were not expecting the result concerning the locati
[normal]on of 
[normal]incidents and subsequently undertook a broader study with a balance of diarists representing a typical traffic mix.
[normal]  
[normal]A diary study of the risk perceptions of road users[bold], HEALTH[bold], RISK &amp; SOCIETY, VOL. 3, NO. 3, 2001, SISSONS JOSHI, SENIOR &amp; SMITH. pp26
[normal]1 – 279
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.4.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal](from 
[normal]Discussion[bold], p 274)
[normal]Data from our previous study suggested that junctions and roundabouts were not perceived
[normal] 
[normal]to be as numerically hazardous by the cycle diarists as would be expected from their
[normal] 
[normal]prominence in local and national accident figures. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A similar picture emerges from this study[bold] [bold]in which only 35.4% of incidents reported by cyclists, and 37.5% of incidents involving[bold] [bold]cyclists reported by other vehicles, occurred at junctions, excluding rou[bold]ndabouts.[bold] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This
[normal] [bold]contrasts with Oxfordshire Road Casualty figures (Oxfordshire County Council, 1993),
[normal] [bold]which report that 68% of cycle accidents occur at junctions. It is well known that cycle
[normal] [bold]accidents are under-represented in accident figures (Mills, 1989)
[normal] but we are addressing here
[normal] [bold]the pattern rather than the absolute number of accidents. National figures (Department of
[normal] [bold]Transport, 1992) also suggest that at least two-thirds of cycle accidents occur at junctions.
[normal]  [bold]We suggest that these official figures almo
[normal]st certainly relate more to the classification of
[normal] [bold]accidents than to the nature of what is happening on the road. The police STATS 19 records
[normal] [bold]classify an accident as occurring at a junction irrespective of whether the manoeuvre of either
[normal] 
[normal]vehicle concerned i
[normal]nvolved the junction or merely happened in the vicinity of a junction.
[normal]  [bold]&#xa0;[bold]With this query in mind, we asked the Department of Transport’s Directorate of Statistics to[bold] [bold]analyse national pedal cycle casualty figures by cross-tabulating cyclists’ actions with [bold]the[bold] [bold]actions of those involved in accidents with them. Of the 25,421 cycle accidents in 1991,[bold] [bold]13.8% involved cyclists turning right or left and a further 28.9% involved other vehicles[bold] [bold]turning right or left. This suggests that only 42.7% of cycle accidents i[bold]nvolve turns at[bold] [bold]junctions, which is considerably closer to estimates in the diary data than the usual two-thirds[bold] [bold]figure quoted[bold].
[normal] [bold]The major manoeuvre of other vehicles which cyclists reported in the current study was[bold] [bold]being overtaken too closely in a straight[bold]-ahead situation[bold]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It is notable that an Australian
[normal] [bold]study, examining the characteristics of fatal as compared to total cycle accidents, finds that
[normal] [bold]fatal accidents are less likely to be at intersections than are non-fatal accidents (Hoque,
[normal] [bold]1990). 
[normal] 
[normal]Our data
[normal] also accord with the British Medical Association’s (1992) review, which
[normal] [bold]comments that most adult cyclist fatalities are caused by a vehicle approaching from
[normal] [bold]behind 
[normal]—which presumably includes errors in overtaking. The Highway Code (Department of
[normal] [bold]Environmen
[normal]t, Transport and the Regions, 1999b) inf
[normal]orms motorists that they should 
[normal]‘give
[normal] [bold][cyclists] at least as much room as you would give a car’ (p. 18), although the accompanying
[normal] [bold]illustration suggests a less generous margin of overtaking than did the illustration 
[normal]in the 1993
[normal] [bold]edition (Department 
[normal]of Transport, 1993). The cyclists in our study clearly felt that they were
[normal] [bold]not given the margin they required by passing motor vehicles, particularly buses. It is possible
[normal] [bold]that buses overtake cycles with no narrower a margin
[normal] than cars do, but threaten cyclists more
[normal] [bold]on account of their greater size. A film record would be needed to establish whether cyclists’
[normal] [bold]perceptions of risk relate more to the size, speed or position of the passing vehicle.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.4.2.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]([bold]from
[normal] Conclusions [bold]Page 277)
[normal]…
[normal]  
[normal]However, while the successful shared use of public space will depend partly on road users’
[normal] 
[normal]attitudes and behaviour, 
[normal]it will also depend on the imaginative implementation of road design[bold] [bold]that can protect the vulnerable from the manoeuvres and speed of the le[bold]ss vulnerable. [bold]&#xa0;[bold]Indeed,
[normal] 
[normal]in his analysis of accident causation, 
[normal]Wagenaar (1992) points out that risk-taking behaviour[bold] 
[normal]can be located predominantly at the strategic end of the system—that is, amongst the[bold] 
[normal]decision makers who structure the system. This [bold]implies that the nature of the risk environment[bold] 
[normal]lies in the hands of those who plan our roads rather than those who use them.[bold] 
[normal]Experience in the Netherlands reveals the extent to which engineering solutions can provide
[normal] 
[normal]a safer space for cyclists and walker
[normal]s
[normal] (Preston, 1990; Tolley, 1990).
[normal]&#xa0;
