[normal]3.6.2.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]For many years divisio
[normal]n
[normal]s
[normal] within cycling advocacy between vehicular cyclists and those who favour better infrastructure 
[normal]are
[normal] deeply unhelpful. Advocating for the wishes of existing cyclists, a minority outlier population, is not the way to make cycling appeal to wider swathes of 
[normal]the population. This does of course result in a tension, as it is not unreasonable for cycling advocacy groups to represent their members, but it is a tension that can I think be fairly easily resolved. There is no need for a dichotomous approach, and it i
[normal]s perfectly feasible to support the needs of existing cyclists while also pushing for decent infrastructure, as well as wider factors that support less confident cyclists.
[normal]3.6.2.3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
